arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMiddle Eastern Minorities and the Arab Spring: Identity and Community in the Twenty-First Century examines eleven minority groups in the early years of the so-called Arab Spring. Wide-ranging in scope, minorities of diverse religious and ethno-linguistic backgrounds are included from North Africa, the Levant, and the Arabian Peninsula. Each has experienced the Arab Spring differently and uniquely depending upon their context. Of particular concern to the international team of scholars involved in this volume, is the interaction and reaction of minorities to the protest movements across the Arab World that called for greater democratic rights and end to respective autocratic regimes. While some minorities participated in the Arab Spring, others were wary of instability and the unintended effects of regime change – notably the rise of violent Islamism. The full effects of the Arab Spring will not be known for years to come, but for the minorities of the Middle East, the immediate future seems certainly tenuous at best.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aArab Spring, 2010-. 0aLinguistic minoritieszMiddle EastxHistoryy21st century. 0aMinoritieszMiddle EastxHistoryy21st century. 0aReligious minoritieszMiddle EastxHistoryy21st century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAbi Chedid, Darina Saliba, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouandel, Youcef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemesmay, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldsmith, Leon T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaidar, Otared, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct